.TH "TEMPORAL.PLAINDATETIME.TOZONEDDATETIME" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.PlainDateTime.toZonedDateTime \-
Temporal.PlainDateTime.prototype.toZonedDateTime()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]toZonedDateTime()\f[B]\f[R] method of
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainDateTime\f[R] instances returns a new
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instance representing the same
date\-time as this plain date\-time, but in the specified time zone.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
toZonedDateTime(timeZone)
toZonedDateTime(timeZone, options)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]timeZone\f[R]
Either a string or a \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instance
representing the time zone to use.
If a \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instance, its time zone is used.
If a string, it can be a named time zone identifier, an offset time zone
identifier, or a date\-time string containing a time zone identifier or
an offset (see time zones and offsets for more information).
.TP
\f[B]options\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An object containing the following property:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]disambiguation\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string specifying what to do when this plain time corresponds to zero
or more than one instants in the time zone, usually because of daylight
saving time shifts.
Possible values are \f[CR]\(dqcompatible\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqearlier\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqlater\(dq\f[R], and
\f[CR]\(dqreject\(dq\f[R].
Defaults to \f[CR]\(dqcompatible\(dq\f[R].
For more information about these values, see ambiguity and gaps from
local time to UTC time.
.RE
.SS Return value
A new \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instance representing the same
date\-time as this plain date\-time, but in the specified time zone.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]RangeError\f[R]
Thrown in one of the following cases:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Any of the options is invalid.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]timeZone\f[R] is not a valid time zone identifier.
.IP \(bu 2
The wall\-clock time is ambiguous in the time zone, and
\f[CR]options.disambiguation\f[R] is set to \f[CR]\(dqreject\(dq\f[R].
.RE
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown if any of the arguments are not of the expected type.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using toZonedDateTime()
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] dt = Temporal.PlainDateTime.from(\(dq2021\-08\-01T12:34:56\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt = dt.toZonedDateTime(\(dqAmerica/New_York\(dq);
console.log(zdt.toString()); \f[I]// \(aq2021\-08\-01T12:34:56\-04:00[America/New_York]\(aq\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] dt2 = Temporal.PlainDateTime.from(\(dq2021\-01\-01T12:34:56\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt2 = dt2.toZonedDateTime(\(dqAmerica/New_York\(dq);
console.log(zdt2.toString()); \f[I]// \(aq2021\-01\-01T12:34:56\-05:00[America/New_York]\(aq\f[R]
.EE
.SS Handling ambiguous times
Below, we have two wall\-clock times that we want to interpret in the
\f[CR]America/New_York\f[R] time zone.
The first one, \f[CR]dtNotExist\f[R], never existed because of a forward
daylight saving time shift, so we need to choose from the times
\f[CR]01:05:00\-05:00\f[R] or \f[CR]03:05:00\-04:00\f[R].
The second one, \f[CR]dtAmbiguous\f[R], appeared twice because of a
backward daylight saving time shift, so we need to choose from the times
\f[CR]01:05:00\-04:00\f[R] or \f[CR]01:05:00\-05:00\f[R].
For a more detailed explanation of this situation, see ambiguity and
gaps from local time to UTC time.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] dtNotExist = Temporal.PlainDateTime.from(\(dq2024\-03\-10T02:05:00\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] dtAmbiguous = Temporal.PlainDateTime.from(\(dq2024\-11\-03T01:05:00\(dq);

\f[I]// Default: compatible\f[R]
console.log(dtNotExist.toZonedDateTime(\(dqAmerica/New_York\(dq).toString());
\f[I]// \(aq2024\-03\-10T03:05:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(aq\f[R]
console.log(dtAmbiguous.toZonedDateTime(\(dqAmerica/New_York\(dq).toString());
\f[I]// \(aq2024\-11\-03T01:05:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(aq\f[R]

\f[I]// Use the earlier time for ambiguous times\f[R]
console.log(
  dtNotExist
    .toZonedDateTime(\(dqAmerica/New_York\(dq, { disambiguation: \(dqearlier\(dq })
    .toString(),
);
\f[I]// \(aq2024\-03\-10T01:05:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(aq\f[R]
console.log(
  dtAmbiguous
    .toZonedDateTime(\(dqAmerica/New_York\(dq, { disambiguation: \(dqearlier\(dq })
    .toString(),
);
\f[I]// \(aq2024\-11\-03T01:05:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(aq\f[R]

\f[I]// Use the later time for ambiguous times\f[R]
console.log(
  dtNotExist
    .toZonedDateTime(\(dqAmerica/New_York\(dq, { disambiguation: \(dqlater\(dq })
    .toString(),
);
\f[I]// \(aq2024\-03\-10T03:05:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(aq\f[R]
console.log(
  dtAmbiguous
    .toZonedDateTime(\(dqAmerica/New_York\(dq, { disambiguation: \(dqlater\(dq })
    .toString(),
);
\f[I]// \(aq2024\-11\-03T01:05:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(aq\f[R]

\f[I]// Throw an error for ambiguous times\f[R]
dtNotExist.toZonedDateTime(\(dqAmerica/New_York\(dq, { disambiguation: \(dqreject\(dq });
\f[I]// RangeError: instant is ambiguous\f[R]
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
